Some of the ransomware operations using this botnet for network access include the infamous Ryuk, Conti, REvil, as well as a new one called Diavol, the Romanian for Devil.{backslash}n{backslash}nSince Emotet’s takedown by law enforcement, Trickbot activity started to increase to such levels that in May it was the most prevalent malware on Check Point’s radar.{backslash}n{backslash}nThe malware maintained its position this month, too, the cybersecurity company notes in a report today, adding that Trickbot’s maintainers are constantly working to improve it.{backslash}n{backslash}nAccording to Check Point’s telemetry, Trickbot impacted 7% of organizations across the world, followed by the XMRig cryptocurrency miner the Formbook info stealer, which affected 3% of the organizations that Check Point monitors worldwide.{backslash}nNew VNC module in the works{backslash}n{backslash}nIn another report, Romanian cybersecurity company Bitdefender says that its systems caught a new version of Trickbot’s VNC module (vncDLL), used after compromising high-profile targets.{backslash}n{backslash}nThe updated module is called tvncDLL and allows the threat actor to monitor the victim and collect information that would enable pivoting to valuable systems on the network.{backslash}n{backslash}nAlthough tvncDLL was discovered on May 12, the Romanian researchers say that it is still under development, “since the group has a frequent update schedule, regularly adding new functionalities and bug fixes.”{backslash}n{backslash}nBitdefender’s analysis of the module points out that it uses a custom communication protocol and reaches the command and control (C2) server through one of nine proxy IP addresses that enable access to victims behind firewalls.{backslash}n{backslash}nTrickbot's tvncDLL module attack overview{backslash}n{backslash}nThe VNC component can stop Trickbot and unload it from memory. When an operator initiates communication, the module creates a virtual desktop with a custom interface.{backslash}n{backslash}n“During normal operation, the alternate desktop is created and fully controlled by the module, copying the icons from the desktop, creating a custom taskbar for managing its processes and creating a custom right-click menu, containing custom functionality,” Bitdefender researchers write in their report.{backslash}n{backslash}nRight click menu for Trickbot’s tvncDLL{backslash}n{backslash}nUsing the command prompt, the threat actor can download fresh payloads from the C2 server, open documents and the email inbox, steal data from the compromised system.{backslash}n{backslash}nAnother option called Native Browser fires up a web browser by taking advantage of the OLE automation feature in Internet Explorer.{backslash}n{backslash}nThe function is under development and its purpose is to steal passwords from Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Opera, and Internet Explorer.{backslash}n{backslash}nTrickbot’s tvncDLL Native Browser feature{backslash}n{backslash}nThe researchers say that while the old vncDLL module has been in use since at least 2018, its successor became active in the wild on May 11, 2021, according to evidence revealed during their investigation.{backslash}n{backslash}nTelemetry data from Bitdefender data shows Trickbot’s C2 servers spread on almost all continents, with the largest number (54) located in North America. According to the company, the number of C2 servers has increased significantly this year, jumping from around 40 in January to more than 140 in June.{backslash}nRelated Articles:{backslash}n{backslash}nSoftware maker removes {backslash}
